= Allow Exiled Dissidents to Come Home

For decades, the Soviet Union has maintained a policy of exiling high profile critics of the regime, up to
and including intellectuals, writers, religious activists and scientists. Some big names include Aleksandr
Solzehnitsyn, who was expelled in 1974 after exposing the gulag system, and biologist Vladimir
Bukovsky who condemned the USSRâ€™s use of psychiatric abuse. Now, under the banner of Glasnost,
many within the party are reviving calls to allow them to return home.

Letting them back would please ideological reformers as well as send a powerful message to the liberal
west that they take their stated policy of openness seriously. Hardliners, however, warn of old wounds
being reopened and the possibility of social unrest.

Do we bring them home?

