@full_return_no_restrictions
title: Full Return Without Restrictions
on-arrival: budget += 2; reformer_approval += 4; moderate_approval += 2; hardliner_approval -= 4; popular_approval += 3; separatism += 2

We permit exiles to return home without placing restrictions on their ability to criticize the regime. Reformers praise the move as being a major step toward cultivating openness. Dissidents and hardliners, however, waste no time criticizing it as being needlessly divisive.

@permit_return_conditions
title: Permit Return, but With Political Conditions
on-arrival: reformer_approval += 2; moderate_approval += 3; hardliner_approval -= 2; popular_approval += 2; separatism += 1

We allow a curated list of dissidents to come home, on the condition that they will not engage in public political activity. Such is a compromise that mildly annoys reform minded politicians as well as the public, who were hoping for more. That said, something is better than nothing.

@maintain_exile
title: Maintain Policy of Exile
on-arrival: budget += 1; reformer_approval -= 4; moderate_approval -= 2; hardliner_approval += 3; popular_approval -= 1

We keep prominent exiles at bay and bar their return home. Reformers denounce the move as a betrayal of Glasnost and the stateâ€™s human rights record remains sour and unchanged. However, hardliners praise the decision as needed to cultivate unity.